TY  - JOUR
T1  - Generalization of Dilworth's Theorem on Minimal Chain Decomposition
AU  - Raghavachari, M.
AU  - Mote, V. L.
Y1  - 1970/03/01
PY  - 1970
DA  - 1970/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.16.7.508
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.16.7.508
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 508
EP  - 511
VL  - 16
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The decomposition of a finite partially ordered set of elements as a union of chains was considered by Dilworth [2]. Dantzig and Hoffman [1] formulated this problem as a linear programming problem and obtained Dilworth's theorem from duality theory. For some practical applications and for a method to obtain a minimal decomposition see Ford and Fulkerson [3]. In this paper we generalize this problem to the case when the set is not necessarily partially ordered and obtain a method of finding a minimal chain decomposition of the set.
AB  - The decomposition of a finite partially ordered set of elements as a union of chains was considered by Dilworth [2]. Dantzig and Hoffman [1] formulated this problem as a linear programming problem and obtained Dilworth's theorem from duality theory. For some practical applications and for a method to obtain a minimal decomposition see Ford and Fulkerson [3]. In this paper we generalize this problem to the case when the set is not necessarily partially ordered and obtain a method of finding a minimal chain decomposition of the set.
